1
00:00:00,655 --> 00:00:17,297
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhudassa

2
00:00:18,914 --> 00:00:32,368
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:36,533 --> 00:00:39,076
I hope you don't draw any meaning from that small hesitation.

4
00:00:43,179 --> 00:00:48,246
The mind suddenly stops.

5
00:00:49,744 --> 00:00:57,697
I just wanted to carry on a little bit with the Buddha's life and something I should have actually said in the last talk, but better late than never.

6
00:00:58,719 --> 00:01:03,405
The idea of spiritual reading as opposed to the way we would normally read.

7
00:01:04,908 --> 00:01:12,359
So we normally read really with an effort to accumulate knowledge, trying to gather information.

8
00:01:12,998 --> 00:01:21,111
But spiritual reading is, I mean for spiritual purposes, was developed I think best by the Benedictines.

9
00:01:21,893 --> 00:01:28,082
And they had these three methods called Lectio, Meditatio and Contemplatio.

10
00:01:28,102 --> 00:01:34,212
So one reads a book, an inspiring book rather than something like a...

11
00:01:34,733 --> 00:01:44,545
say a book by Ajahn Chah or something like that, which is written from the heart rather than an academic book, although even academic books can inspire.

12
00:01:46,628 --> 00:01:50,212
And you read it as if you're reading poetry or listening to music.

13
00:01:51,293 --> 00:01:54,596
You're reading along and, of course, it's going in, whatever you're saying.

14
00:01:55,317 --> 00:01:57,501
And every so often there'll be a paragraph.

15
00:01:58,138 --> 00:02:02,546
a sentence or a phrase which seems to hit, to sort of catch you.

16
00:02:04,069 --> 00:02:09,157
And what you do is you keep repeating that until, as it were, you've absorbed it.

17
00:02:09,377 --> 00:02:14,165
Like you might listen to a piece of music over and over again or read a poem over and over again.

18
00:02:14,826 --> 00:02:15,929
You're not thinking about it.

19
00:02:17,191 --> 00:02:21,919
You're allowing the heart to grasp it, you might say, sort of an intuitive feel.

20
00:02:24,885 --> 00:02:28,311
And then when you feel you've had enough of that, you just stop still.

21
00:02:29,372 --> 00:02:33,179
And maybe some thoughts come around it, some ideas, some thoughts.

22
00:02:34,259 --> 00:02:36,544
So you can follow them for a little while and develop them.

23
00:02:36,963 --> 00:02:40,669
And then you just drop them and you fall into silence.

24
00:02:40,689 --> 00:02:41,912
And then you go to the next passage.

25
00:02:43,615 --> 00:02:49,903
And what you may find is it has an inspiring effect.

26
00:02:49,984 --> 00:02:52,328
It makes you want to go and sit, as it were.

27
00:02:53,050 --> 00:02:58,697
And it's interesting because it pops out when you're talking every so often.

28
00:02:59,538 --> 00:03:05,825
You haven't tried to remember it or anything, but it's there, as it were, more deeply absorbed.

29
00:03:08,829 --> 00:03:21,824
And in a sense, that's the purpose, really, isn't it, of all art, is to allow us to re-experience in our own way what somebody else has experienced.

30
00:03:23,122 --> 00:03:24,063
T.S.

31
00:03:24,084 --> 00:03:29,012
Eliot called it the objective correlative.

32
00:03:29,032 --> 00:03:29,633
Need I explain?

33
00:03:31,917 --> 00:03:39,830
What he meant by that, as I understand it anyway, was that I have an experience and I want to pass it on to you.

34
00:03:40,705 --> 00:03:50,236
I have to find some symbolic way in which your heart and mind can, as it were, communicate with me or with my mind.

35
00:03:50,276 --> 00:04:02,132
So I have an idea, say music, it comes out as a feeling, say joy for a start, as something different.

36
00:04:02,512 --> 00:04:10,442
So joy comes up in the heart and I'm a musician and so I want to express that joy and express it through a certain medium.

37
00:04:11,231 --> 00:04:14,555
And it's specific culturally, isn't it?

38
00:04:14,935 --> 00:04:30,728
Unless you've listened to, say, Chinese or Japanese music or even Indian music, you've got to get into that symbolism, that way of expressing these particular emotions and understandings, music understanding.

39
00:04:30,749 --> 00:04:37,815
And that way, we two people can communicate at a deeper level than just an intellectual level.

40
00:04:37,836 --> 00:04:40,598
If I say I'm depressed, that's one thing.

41
00:04:40,848 --> 00:04:48,036
But if I write a piece of music that makes you depressed, then we have some deeper communication.

42
00:04:48,817 --> 00:04:59,007
So when I'm going through the life of the Buddha here, I'm really just allowing thoughts to arise in that way and just to see what comes up.

43
00:04:59,588 --> 00:05:07,497
And often when I go through the same thing, different thoughts come up because other information from somewhere else has come in and other feelings come up.

44
00:05:07,516 --> 00:05:07,817
So

45
00:05:08,168 --> 00:05:15,516
Every time I reread the life of the Buddha, there's always something new comes up for me around it.

46
00:05:17,016 --> 00:05:20,341
So this isn't an academic approach.

47
00:05:21,041 --> 00:05:33,134
Whether it's history or myth, it's in a sense immaterial because it lies there within the Buddhist tradition as a sort of archetype, as an exemplar whom we're following.

48
00:05:33,154 --> 00:05:35,836
And anyway, I'm not an academic.

49
00:05:36,158 --> 00:05:37,399
I'm a would-be academic.

50
00:05:37,952 --> 00:05:41,298
So you have to take everything I say with a pinch of salt.

51
00:05:44,163 --> 00:05:50,154
So the first thing is that we got to the point where he was about to be born.

52
00:05:51,377 --> 00:05:56,906
And he was born somewhere around 2,300, 2,500 years ago.

53
00:05:58,843 --> 00:06:11,557
And when you consider that, the length of time, and you consider how many religious leaders have probably appeared, started something, and then their offering, their teaching has sort of disappeared.

54
00:06:13,178 --> 00:06:16,262
One example of that would be, say, the Jains.

55
00:06:17,043 --> 00:06:27,535
The Jains, if you look at the ancient maps, were, I think, just about as numerous at some point, maybe even more numerous than Buddhists in India.

56
00:06:28,341 --> 00:06:35,774
But somehow they fizzled out and are now down to somewhere around 3 million, which in the population of India is very small.

57
00:06:37,276 --> 00:06:46,632
Which doesn't mean that the teachings of the Nagantha were wrong or anything like that, but there's obviously some feeling there of fading out.

58
00:06:46,673 --> 00:06:48,274
I mean, it may grow again.

59
00:06:48,795 --> 00:06:54,045
But there's lots of little religions, and especially these days, you know, with gurus popping up here and there,

60
00:06:54,952 --> 00:06:59,536
And then that sudden rush of interest and it builds up and then it slowly sort of dies away.

61
00:07:02,759 --> 00:07:11,507
So when you think that this is a 2,500-year-old tradition, you know, that inspires faith and inspires a certain trust.

62
00:07:12,108 --> 00:07:15,831
So remember that faith in our understanding is not a belief.

63
00:07:16,132 --> 00:07:18,574
A belief is putting faith in a statement.

64
00:07:18,593 --> 00:07:23,778
So if you were to say, I believe the Buddha was enlightened, you're in great danger of being deluded.

65
00:07:25,480 --> 00:07:32,771
There's a difference in believing it, in believing that statement, and in trusting it.

66
00:07:33,612 --> 00:07:35,175
And in a sense, we don't know, do we?

67
00:07:35,295 --> 00:07:39,062
We don't know what the hell he was talking about until we get there.

68
00:07:39,083 --> 00:07:41,586
And when we get there, we don't know whether it's the end.

69
00:07:41,966 --> 00:07:42,928
There may be something more.

70
00:07:42,949 --> 00:07:43,350
Who knows?

71
00:07:43,971 --> 00:07:45,413
So it's a case of

72
00:07:45,713 --> 00:07:51,581
trusting, and the trust grows as we practice because we get the benefits of it.

73
00:07:51,882 --> 00:08:08,706
And that leads us towards that goal and hopefully we get a peak of it, a little touch of it, and then at that point that faith becomes immovable because now we've had a taste of that end that we're moving towards.

74
00:08:10,127 --> 00:08:14,134
So when we consider that for 2,500 years millions of people

75
00:08:14,536 --> 00:08:23,548
have been practicing in this way and have been considering the life of the Buddha, and it's affected them, and cultures have grown around it.

76
00:08:24,589 --> 00:08:38,749
One, it's part of the basis of our faith, the fact that it's been such a long and deep tradition, and that it's spread over cultures.

77
00:08:39,250 --> 00:08:43,075
So obviously similar to Christianity and Islam,

78
00:08:44,083 --> 00:08:53,833
which have been able to go beyond greatly their cultural bounds and move into different cultures, being developed by them in their own way.

79
00:08:54,794 --> 00:09:01,061
And so there is, I think, that trust comes with something which has such an ancient history.

80
00:09:03,903 --> 00:09:09,349
So that's something that, you see, in the sense of this meditazione and all that sort of stuff, one,

81
00:09:10,222 --> 00:09:13,206
Thinking of that, it raises that feeling of faith.

82
00:09:13,265 --> 00:09:15,148
It raises that feeling of trust, you see.

83
00:09:16,028 --> 00:09:17,009
And you sort of stay with it.

84
00:09:17,350 --> 00:09:19,331
You sort of delight in it, you see.

85
00:09:20,352 --> 00:09:24,356
So remember that part of our practice is going through all this hell stuff.

86
00:09:24,376 --> 00:09:27,759
But the other part is developing what is beautiful in us.

87
00:09:29,361 --> 00:09:31,583
Just when something joyful comes up, don't kick it out.

88
00:09:33,905 --> 00:09:36,288
Say, oh, where's all my depressions and anxieties?

89
00:09:37,409 --> 00:09:38,931
It's a case of when

90
00:09:39,282 --> 00:09:54,282
if you're reading, say, in the library or you're listening to a tape and suddenly you get this lovely PT come up, this joy around the teaching or this interest, you see, then stop the tape, stop the book, you know, and just stay with it, you know, and let the heart absorb it.

91
00:09:54,461 --> 00:09:56,565
Don't sort of rush through it, as it were.

92
00:09:59,948 --> 00:10:06,116
That age, of course, just as an aside, was quite an age for human beings because at the same time there was Moses,

93
00:10:06,923 --> 00:10:09,765
It was Lao Tzu in China, Socrates.

94
00:10:10,386 --> 00:10:13,029
And it's known in the history books as the Axial Age.

95
00:10:13,071 --> 00:10:15,693
Something happened in human consciousness.

96
00:10:15,894 --> 00:10:18,557
Something moved, something turned.

97
00:10:20,440 --> 00:10:23,383
And from that you can say history begins.

98
00:10:23,562 --> 00:10:26,407
Written history, the history that we know, actually begins around about that time.

99
00:10:27,447 --> 00:10:30,432
History in India begins with the life of the Buddha, frankly.

100
00:10:30,751 --> 00:10:32,214
That's when it begins at that time.

101
00:10:33,475 --> 00:10:34,736
History in the sense of facts begins.

102
00:10:39,796 --> 00:10:50,211
So anyway, he's born, and being a very advanced being, he's chosen his mother and father, and seems to have chosen rather well.

103
00:10:50,873 --> 00:11:00,488
He's a local potentate, and his mother also belongs to a family which is also rich and powerful.

104
00:11:00,889 --> 00:11:05,495
He's got the good karma there, you see.

105
00:11:05,515 --> 00:11:13,767
And as you know, she wants to go home to have her child, and he's born under these Sala trees on the way.

106
00:11:14,047 --> 00:11:16,049
She gives birth in the park at Lumbini.

107
00:11:17,491 --> 00:11:18,774
So this is the theme, isn't it?

108
00:11:19,114 --> 00:11:20,216
The Buddha and nature.

109
00:11:20,515 --> 00:11:26,003
He's born under a tree, he's given the light under a tree, and he finally dies under a tree.

110
00:11:27,004 --> 00:11:28,787
And that sort of connection...

111
00:11:29,323 --> 00:11:42,083
with nature, something that in our society, obviously, you can lose, especially living in a city.

112
00:11:42,104 --> 00:11:48,114
I remember I was once out in a meditation center and this little chick had fallen on the ground.

113
00:11:48,494 --> 00:11:50,256
It had fallen out of a nest.

114
00:11:51,197 --> 00:11:54,082
And being a townie, I just looked at it and wondered what to do, you see.

115
00:11:55,565 --> 00:11:58,748
And I'm looking at this chick thinking, now, what do I do with this, you see?

116
00:11:59,188 --> 00:12:04,594
So I went down to pick it up and put it on the wall just in case the cat would take it, you see.

117
00:12:05,195 --> 00:12:10,679
And as I bent down to pick it up, it sort of bit at me and I sort of leapt out of my skin.

118
00:12:12,522 --> 00:12:15,445
This little tiny little bird's scaring me to hell.

119
00:12:15,465 --> 00:12:20,610
So eventually I did finally get it on the wall and I don't know what happened to the little thing.

120
00:12:22,143 --> 00:12:27,049
And I was saying afterwards, probably if I'd have found that in the town, I'd have probably stamped on it and put it in the bin.

121
00:12:29,092 --> 00:12:32,998
That's how detached you can become from living beings and nature.

122
00:12:34,440 --> 00:12:40,908
So, again, it's a case of just recollecting on those things and what nature means to us.

123
00:12:41,850 --> 00:12:46,576
Walking in nature, being close to it, hugging a tree occasionally.

124
00:12:48,318 --> 00:12:50,142
How close are we to

125
00:12:50,527 --> 00:12:53,672
to the ground, to the actual earth that we live on.

126
00:12:54,272 --> 00:13:05,649
Do we ever sit and consider how we are utterly dependent on what the earth is giving us in terms of the produce of the ground?

127
00:13:06,089 --> 00:13:10,316
The air that we breathe, things like that.

128
00:13:10,355 --> 00:13:11,537
The water that we drink.

129
00:13:11,717 --> 00:13:16,904
And that understanding of the body being...

130
00:13:17,188 --> 00:13:44,174
just in this constant change of it's like a double edged fountain with stuff coming in on one aperture and then escaping through all the rest and you get the feeling of the body not being at all static but this flow it's actually in a state of flow it's digesting and giving away and receiving and digesting and giving away so you get this

131
00:13:44,341 --> 00:13:48,645
This feeling of being a little bit part of that process that we see in nature.

132
00:13:56,375 --> 00:14:04,505
Then, of course, it's a consideration to think about the importance of our parents.

133
00:14:06,327 --> 00:14:08,250
So he's chosen these two people.

134
00:14:08,390 --> 00:14:14,077
Well, I doubt if we chose the people whom we ended up being born to.

135
00:14:14,378 --> 00:14:43,895
and just to recollect what we owe our parents that sort of usually we hold on to the more sticky bad memories that we have of them but when you consider what our parents actually did for us then you come to the conclusion of the Buddha that even if you were to carry your mother and father on your shoulders all your life you would not have repaid them their gift even if they kicked you around a lot

136
00:14:44,432 --> 00:14:45,114
You're still here.

137
00:14:45,514 --> 00:14:46,034
You made it.

138
00:14:49,238 --> 00:15:06,736
And parents being so much part of our makeup, even the little habits we have, just the way that we do things, we pick up from our mother and father, just that intimacy that we have, especially with our mothers.

139
00:15:09,058 --> 00:15:12,582
And then, of course, his mother dies within a week.

140
00:15:13,423 --> 00:15:17,831
So one wonders what effect that might have had on a weak old baby.

141
00:15:19,033 --> 00:15:21,256
We know that the intimacy is already there.

142
00:15:21,277 --> 00:15:22,399
It's already there in the womb.

143
00:15:23,080 --> 00:15:26,785
The child actually knows the mother's voice, the feel of the mother.

144
00:15:27,586 --> 00:15:32,514
And having tasted her milk and got close to her, and then suddenly there's a change.

145
00:15:32,615 --> 00:15:34,138
There's a change of environment.

146
00:15:34,597 --> 00:15:40,528
And although it's her mother's sister, one wonders whether there's...

147
00:15:40,761 --> 00:15:44,044
how that early child would have been affected by that.

148
00:15:45,005 --> 00:16:04,024
Knowing later on what identity crisis he goes through, his existential crisis, sickness, old age and death, there's a suggestion from our own in-depth psychology that this was the beginning of his suffering in terms of that awakening to loss.

149
00:16:05,405 --> 00:16:06,567
Never mind the birth process.

150
00:16:13,769 --> 00:16:22,563
So now he's born, and the next thing is, of course, is that he is recognized by the seer, the asceter.

151
00:16:23,365 --> 00:16:32,500
And the asceter says he's either going to be a world-conquering monarch, or he's going to be fully enlightened, a fully self-enlightened being.

152
00:16:32,519 --> 00:16:39,692
This business of the world-conquering monarch is like an alter ego that sort of runs through the scriptures.

153
00:16:40,312 --> 00:16:48,202
there's always a picture of this monarch who rules the world out of the Dharma by way of the precepts.

154
00:16:49,063 --> 00:16:54,570
And it runs almost, you might say, concurrent with the idea of the Buddha being the fully self-enlightened being.

155
00:16:54,629 --> 00:17:00,057
In other words, if he hadn't have chosen that path, this is what he would have done.

156
00:17:00,076 --> 00:17:09,087
He would have set his horse loose, this is the way he did it, and followed his horse, and wherever the horse went, he'd have conquered, and eventually the whole world would have been brought under his Dharma rule.

157
00:17:10,907 --> 00:17:18,576
The story about the Chakravartins is that finally one of them doesn't keep the precepts and the whole thing begins to collapse.

158
00:17:19,458 --> 00:17:30,751
And there's one discourse which is rather interesting from a modern point of view, well, from any point of view, but specifically these days, and that is that poverty is the root of social evil.

159
00:17:31,291 --> 00:17:33,935
That's what the particular discourse says.

160
00:17:34,715 --> 00:17:40,222
And that's something also that we can sort of think about.

161
00:17:42,463 --> 00:17:49,712
But this idea of the split within us between the worldly life and the spiritual life, see, that stays with us all the way, doesn't it?

162
00:17:50,133 --> 00:17:51,173
That stays with us all the way.

163
00:17:52,115 --> 00:18:03,749
And there's a... Not to say that we're going to become world-conquering monarchs, but there's always that pull towards the world, you see.

164
00:18:04,630 --> 00:18:05,270
What is the world?

165
00:18:05,330 --> 00:18:06,172
It's riches, isn't it?

166
00:18:06,251 --> 00:18:10,277
Riches, power, fame...

167
00:18:10,747 --> 00:18:13,970
and sensual pleasures, you know, the pleasures of life.

168
00:18:13,990 --> 00:18:30,163
And so even here, you see, you know, when you're doing your meditation and you get that feeling, really, which is not sustainable from the body's point of view, that you might have a cup of tea and there's no need for it, and then you might say, oh, there's the world-conquering monarch, you see.

169
00:18:31,044 --> 00:18:31,924
I have to let go of that.

170
00:18:33,425 --> 00:18:34,987
And then I get back onto your seat.

171
00:18:36,888 --> 00:18:40,652
So if you consider that there's always that split within us, you know,

172
00:18:41,019 --> 00:18:45,153
one of renouncing the world and one of being dragged away into it.

173
00:18:45,977 --> 00:18:49,388
And it's just good to see it in these terms.

174
00:18:49,710 --> 00:18:53,763
So here the Buddha has been prophesied that he's going to take the one or the other.

175
00:19:00,275 --> 00:19:07,262
So now he's brought up in a very worldly way.

176
00:19:07,762 --> 00:19:11,948
So once his father knows that he could shoot off and become an ascetic, he definitely doesn't want that.

177
00:19:12,008 --> 00:19:15,090
He wants him to follow him in the family and build up the empire.

178
00:19:17,452 --> 00:19:22,118
He surrounds him with pleasures, basically.

179
00:19:22,159 --> 00:19:24,361
This is the tale.

180
00:19:24,381 --> 00:19:27,243
But I would have thought that his particular group, the

181
00:19:27,612 --> 00:19:33,383
the warrior caste, the Kshatriya caste, which were the dominant caste in that part of India.

182
00:19:33,844 --> 00:19:37,511
As you move towards what is now Bengal, it would have been the Brahmins.

183
00:19:38,272 --> 00:19:42,842
But in his part of India, it was definitely the warrior caste, which were the top caste.

184
00:19:44,846 --> 00:19:49,214
That's why you'll see him always taking the mickey out of the Brahmins in me.

185
00:19:49,599 --> 00:19:53,064
In the scriptures, he always says, well, a true Brahmin does this and does that.

186
00:19:53,084 --> 00:19:53,765
He doesn't do this.

187
00:19:54,846 --> 00:19:57,630
He never talks about the warrior caste.

188
00:19:57,690 --> 00:19:59,813
The true warrior caste is always the Brahmin.

189
00:20:01,535 --> 00:20:03,676
So he's knifing occasionally.

190
00:20:05,880 --> 00:20:09,023
In, of course, a very compassionate way, I'm suggesting.

191
00:20:12,288 --> 00:20:15,372
It's usually, of course, Brahmins that are approaching him when he's talking about Brahmins.

192
00:20:18,472 --> 00:20:26,963
So he's there in his palaces, and we go through this whole business of an identity crisis.

193
00:20:27,324 --> 00:20:32,631
So it's very interesting, really, from a point of view of the general growth of our psychology.

194
00:20:33,751 --> 00:20:35,453
He's married around about the age of 16.

195
00:20:35,493 --> 00:20:37,576
This is the myth, which would have been normal in those days.

196
00:20:37,616 --> 00:20:40,540
We know in India you get married pretty soon.

197
00:20:40,560 --> 00:20:45,527
And somewhere in his mid-20s, I would have thought,

198
00:20:45,575 --> 00:20:48,659
And this happens, I think, to a lot of people.

199
00:20:51,042 --> 00:20:58,173
You know, it's the first sort of crisis in life about leaving go, letting go, like youth is passing.

200
00:20:58,574 --> 00:21:04,662
There's something within the person which is saying, actually, let's get serious.

201
00:21:05,182 --> 00:21:10,029
So it's usually around about 25 onwards that people get married, they get a job,

