He was one of my...

408
00:39:53,242 --> 00:40:03,753
a French existentialist writer, actually wrote a book called Sisyphus, in which this became a motif for the absurdity of life.

409
00:40:03,773 --> 00:40:17,108
If you really, really believe all there is, is annihilation, why get up in the morning to roll that boulder up the hill, and go to sleep, and then let it roll down again, and the next morning you're going to roll it back up the hill?

410
00:40:18,487 --> 00:40:38,967
And when he was absolutely at one with this idea of the absurdity of suffering, which I think the existentialists understood very well, they definitely understood the first noble truth, he said that the only dignified way to approach this problem was to commit suicide.

411
00:40:39,608 --> 00:40:40,309
That was his answer.

412
00:40:41,750 --> 00:40:47,735
Luckily, he did not have to follow his own thought too much because he sadly died in a car crash.

413
00:40:47,918 --> 00:41:17,824
in 1956 he didn't have to take his logic into action you might say so this idea of death especially death the whole process of dying of illness of growing old and then dying unless there is some understanding then you have this you have to really face the whole thing of annihilation

414
00:41:18,766 --> 00:41:44,925
And in last week when I was answering a question about afterlife and rebirth and all that sort of stuff, one thing I like to say is that in terms of the Buddhist teaching, the people who don't believe anything's going to happen when they die are, in my estimation, much more closer to becoming liberated than the people who are.

415
00:41:45,664 --> 00:41:50,411
for the simple reason that when we believe something is going to go on, it comforts us.

416
00:41:52,795 --> 00:42:01,547
The self feels comfort in the fact that, oh, when I die, I shall be born, I'll be happy if I'm born a rat, as long as I'm born, as long as I keep going, this I.

417
00:42:02,208 --> 00:42:08,117
And so there's never facing the collapse of the self, which happens at death.

418
00:42:08,277 --> 00:42:09,659
I mean, that's supposed to happen.

419
00:42:10,882 --> 00:42:15,367
And even, I think, Muhammad said, you have to die before you die,

420
00:42:15,836 --> 00:42:17,199
You have to die before you die.

421
00:42:18,000 --> 00:42:20,943
And I think even Christ put it in some sort of way.

422
00:42:20,963 --> 00:42:24,329
Unless you are born again, he put it in a more positive way.

423
00:42:24,349 --> 00:42:26,112
That's right, you will not enter into the kingdom of heaven.

424
00:42:26,132 --> 00:42:27,333
You will not be born again.

425
00:42:27,994 --> 00:42:42,434
So there's something about facing the horror of that point of complete loss of self, which is death, which is part of the process of our liberation.

426
00:42:43,242 --> 00:42:49,447
And he was so shook by this that, of course, he decided to leave home.

427
00:42:57,155 --> 00:43:08,686
So in your meditation, when these fears come up, you see, these fears of sickness, old age, and death, go into them.

428
00:43:08,846 --> 00:43:10,768
They've come as messengers from the gods.

429
00:43:11,068 --> 00:43:12,690
They're there to awaken us.

430
00:43:13,271 --> 00:43:18,139
And remember that it's all delusion.

431
00:43:18,159 --> 00:43:19,782
It's all symbolic in the mind.

432
00:43:20,422 --> 00:43:28,996
You have to, as it were, remember, always go beneath the thought, beneath the image, to the viscera, to the actual mental state that's driving it.

433
00:43:29,737 --> 00:43:36,166
You have to go into that fear, feel, feel it, get accustomed to it, get comfortable with fear.

434
00:43:36,768 --> 00:43:36,907
Mm-hmm.

435
00:43:37,528 --> 00:43:40,032
and really allow it to express itself.

436
00:43:41,195 --> 00:43:46,322
Because this fear, remember, is always generated out of that delusion of self.

437
00:43:47,304 --> 00:43:52,351
And as we become accustomed to fear, that's Mara.

438
00:43:52,391 --> 00:43:55,996
That's the expression of our fear, expression of our delusion.

439
00:43:56,358 --> 00:44:02,507
So as we become accustomed to fear, then of course the sense of self is disappearing.

440
00:44:03,262 --> 00:44:07,548
The sense of self manifests through these negative states.

441
00:44:08,210 --> 00:44:10,653
But as we become accustomed to them, we see them.

442
00:44:10,673 --> 00:44:16,222
If you remember Mara, when he attacked the Buddha every so often, Mara had to slink away because the Buddha saw him.

443
00:44:16,663 --> 00:44:27,820
Seeing, feeling those emotions, burying ourselves in them, seeing them even going beyond the idea of an emotion, beyond the idea of a feeling, to the constituents themselves.

444
00:44:28,913 --> 00:44:39,525
you know, like the feeling of sickness, the feeling of tightness, the nausea, getting right down to the physical level, and in so doing, it's a process of depersonalizing.

445
00:44:40,106 --> 00:44:42,289
You are depersonalizing the process.

446
00:44:43,891 --> 00:44:48,898
And that, of course, eventually relieves us, and hopefully we can stay steady in fear.

447
00:44:49,398 --> 00:44:53,463
So once we've lost our fear of fear, what is to frighten us?

448
00:44:54,123 --> 00:44:58,650
And I shall quote your own very great president, Roosevelt, who said...

449
00:44:59,811 --> 00:45:02,157
What are we to fear but fear?

450
00:45:02,257 --> 00:45:03,621
I think I've correctly...

451
00:45:05,505 --> 00:45:15,829
So I'd like to bring our little talk to an end there and I'm going to in one of the times anyway

452
00:45:16,079 --> 00:45:31,085
I want to do an exercise rather than give a talk on looking at the body, an exercise of looking at our relationship to the body, our feelings of disgust with the body and all that.

453
00:45:31,146 --> 00:45:34,913
These are exercises that come out of the Satipatthana discourse.

454
00:45:34,932 --> 00:45:40,702
And then to move it just towards the end, towards a little new age input of healing.

455
00:45:41,677 --> 00:45:49,112
And I'll tell you when I'm doing it, so if you're not particularly attracted to that, you needn't come.

456
00:45:51,757 --> 00:46:01,155
Because somehow we have to find a way of making this deeply meaningful to us in ourselves, rather than it just being stories, as it were.

457
00:46:03,615 --> 00:46:13,440
So I can only hope that my words have been of some assistance to you and I can only hope that even by the end of this course you will be fully liberated.

